### Steps to Reproduce

1. Create a View component that listens to the responder system gestures.
2. Give this View as a child a WebView.
3. Make sure the View and WebView have the same dimensions.
4. Run the project on a device and try to touch/drag the views.

### Expected Behavior

The onResponder* functions of the View should fire when the user touches or drags the screen where the views are displayed.

### Actual Behavior

None of the `onResponder*` functions or `on*ShouldSetResponder*` functions fire.

### Reproducible Demo

  ```
import { View, WebView } from 'react-native';

  ...

  returnTrue = () => true;

  returnFalse = () => false;

  startDrag = () => {
    console.warn('startDrag');
    ...
    return true;
  };

  dragging = () => {
    console.warn('dragging');
    ...
    return true;
  };

  render() {
    const { width, height } = this.props;

    return (
      <View
        onMoveShouldSetResponder={this.returnTrue}
        onMoveShouldSetResponderCapture={this.returnTrue}
        onResponderGrant={this.startDrag}
        onResponderMove={this.dragging}
        onResponderReject={this.returnTrue}
        onResponderRelease={this.returnTrue}
        onResponderTerminate={this.returnTrue}
        onResponderTerminationRequest={this.returnFalse}
        onStartShouldSetResponder={this.returnTrue}
        onStartShouldSetResponderCapture={this.returnTrue}
        style={{ width, height }}
      >
        <WebView
          originWhitelist={['*']}
          scalesPageToFit
          scrollEnabled={false}
          javaScriptEnabled={false}
          style={{ width, height }}
        />
      </View>
    );
  }

...

```

This code works on Android (iOS not tested yet).
